accounts of the period. In addition to a careful examination of the greatly extended manuscript tradition, the editor's critical analysis explores Baldric's career; his writing style; the dating and reception of his text; the amplification of the language, narrative and characters found in his recapitulation of his primary source, the Gesta Francorum; the influence of the text on medieval authors from Orderic Vitalis to Humbert of Romans; and its perspective on the crusade as a means of protecting the familia Christi . Dr STEVEN BIDDLECOMBE has taught widely in a number of universities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Latin.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCrusadesyFirst, 1096-1099vEarly works to 1800. 0aCrusadesyFirst, 1096-1099vSources. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBaldric of Bourgeil.  aDr STEVEN BIDDLECOMBE.  aFirst Crusade.  aGesta Francorum.  aHistoria Ierosolimitana.  aHumbert of Romans.  aOrderic Vitalis.  aUniversity of Wisconsin, Madison.  acrusade accounts.  afamilia Christi.  amanuscript tradition.  amedieval authors.1 aBiddlecombe, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204359140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782043591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782043591/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles